Refining and improving models should be the goal of the original bittensor whitepaper, however, I have yet to see any results spanning from that effort. In fact, the closest I have been were models being finetuned for high scoring on the reward models.

Finetuning from the network is something that I have been talking about since I joined, and waited on since Finney, but the potential is simply not there. What we currently have can best be described as a collection of "Mixture of Experts", a multitude of AI models that each provide enough information about the subject you want to give, however due to the way the blockchain works, they are trying to outcompete each other. Each network tries to be better than the other. This will not (and I repeat it once again) provide an actual AGI like many like to claim, in fact you are just creating a competitor for openAI. The bittensor "AGI" is simply an AI model trying to get the highest ranking. There is no human bias, there is no "generalistic" idea on how the AI should behave, in fact, I am unsure if I can actually sell access to my validator and make a profit out of it. Its cheaper to run a service myself, than to witness the network slowly killing me.

If you really want to see finetuning, look at Lazarus. That one I financially backed with funds from Tensor.Exchange. It recently got mentioned in a paper about "finetuning models" as a really cheap & fast way to make better models, and the results we had from that model gave some great insights in AI model behaviour. Compared to our brain its small, but the way we built it caused all known records on huggingface to be broken. Why? Because the team fully understands AI models and constantly improves them into better mixtures. The reason we haven't deployed our latest finetunes on bittensor? They suck on the bittensor network, due to fundamental issues in the reward system.

Because Bittensor is still small (and only 1 subnet incentivized), one very smart miner can dominate as to make it more centralized.

With more subnets, smart miners must specialize to maintain comp. advantage and win in their preferred subnet, or choose to spread out between subnets.
